4.45/5  rDev +0.2%look: 4 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.5Drank from a 25.4 fl oz (750 ml) bottle purchased at Craft Beer Cellar, Belmont, MA
01/19/16
Served in a pint glass
The beer poured a turbid, dull orangey-amber color. This looked exactly like orange juice. A fluffy, frothy, bright white, two finger tall crown topped the body. The head slowly faded to a lasting cap of foam. A few large, odd shaped patches of lacing stuck along the glass.
Lots of interesting stuff happening in the aroma. Weed-like notes dominated initially. The beer smelled almost like straight fresh bud. As the beer sat, citrus notes also became quite apparent. Lots of lime juice. Crisp and zesty. Orange peel also came through strong. There was a generic tutti fruity quality as well. Mango appeared as the beer warmed. The tropical fruit notes continued to intensify. Some peach came forth as well.
The flavor profile was also impressive and very similar to the nose. Citrus notes dominated. Lots of fresh orange juice, orange peel, tangerine and zesty lime. A bit margarita-like. Tropical fruits were rather apparent. Mango was most noticeable. Bit of pineapple. Some sweetened white grapefruit appeared on the back end. Orange rind came through in the finish. Hint of pithy bitterness. All in all, really juicy and immensely drinkable.
The mouthfeel was classic Trillium but perhaps a touch lighter than anticipated given the style. Super soft and plush on the palate. Creamy, slick and smooth. The liquid contained a fine, subtle effervescence.
Double Dry Hopped Scaled is a flavorful and supremely crushable IPA, but it is definitely a few notches below Trillium's best work. The strong lime notes and citrusy tanginess set this one apart from most of their other hoppy offerings. 1,715 charactersDamian, Feb 01, 2016
